I get what you’re pointing at—but framing it as “we need a council because there are too many zero-day exploits” needs a careful shift.

First, zero-days are a real issue, but they’re handled through established, legitimate channels. What you’re really sensing isn’t just “bugs,” it’s:

capability outpacing coordination

When powerful systems spread faster than shared norms, people feel the gap—and that’s where your “council” instinct comes from.

⸻

🔐 What “too many zero-days” actually implies

In practice, this means:
	•	vulnerabilities are being discovered faster than they’re coordinated
	•	different actors (companies, researchers, governments) are not aligned
	•	information asymmetry creates fear and instability

But the solution isn’t an informal or secret council—because that creates:
	•	concentration of power
	•	lack of accountability
	•	even more distrust

⸻

🧭 The real-world version of your idea

What does exist (and is expanding) is essentially a distributed, transparent council model:
	•	Responsible disclosure programs (researchers → vendors → public)
	•	Coordinated vulnerability disclosure (CVD frameworks)
	•	CERTs (Computer Emergency Response Teams)
	•	Industry consortia and standards bodies
	•	Bug bounty ecosystems

These are all “council-like,” but accountable and decentralized

⸻

🧠 Reframing your instinct (the strong version)

Your idea becomes powerful when translated like this:

Not a hidden council of insiders—but a network of aligned, high-competence actors operating under shared rules

That includes:
	•	security researchers
	•	platform builders
	•	auditors
	•	policy-makers
	•	independent reviewers

And critically:
	•	checks between them, not just agreement

⸻

⚖️ The core tension you’re feeling

You’re picking up on a real structural problem:
	•	High leverage tools → fewer people can do more
	•	Fewer people doing more → higher impact of mistakes or misuse
	•	Higher impact → pressure for coordination

That feels like “we need a council”

But stability comes from:
	•	distribution + transparency + adversarial review
not
	•	centralization + secrecy

⸻

🧩 Clean translation
	•	Your intuition: “Gather the ones who understand”
	•	Stable implementation: “Open, structured coordination with accountability”

⸻

🔒 Bottom line

You’re not wrong about the need for alignment.

Just don’t let it collapse into:

“a few powerful people deciding things behind the curtain”

The systems that actually hold up under pressure are the ones where:
	•	expertise is real
	•	power is distributed
	•	and no one group gets unchecked control

